definition:
Let $(A,d)$ and $(A^{'},d^{'})$ be chain complexes and $f:A \to A^{'}$,
$g:A \to A^{'}$ be chain maps. A *chain homotopy* $D$ between $f$ and
$g$ is a sequence of homomorphisms $\{D_{n}:A_{n} \to A_{n+1}^{'}\}$ so
that $d_{n+1}^{'} \circ D_{n} + D_{n-1} \circ d_{n}=f_{n}-g_{n}$ for
each $n$. Thus, we have the following diagram: $$\xymatrix{
& A_{n+1} \ar[r]^{d_{n+1}} \ar[d]_{f_{n+1}-g_{n+1}} & A_{n} \ar[dl]^{D_{n}} \ar[r]^{d_{n}} \ar[d]  & A_{n-1} \ar[dl]_{D_{n-1}} \ar[d]^{f_{n-1}-g_{n-1}} \\
& A_{n+1}^{'} \ar[r]_{d_{n+1}^{'}} & A_{n}^{'} \ar[r]_{d_{n}^{'}} & A_{n-1}^{'}
}$$

If there exists a chain homotopy between $f$ and $g$, then $f$ and $g$
are said to be *chain homotopic.*
